    {
      "id": "9956b556ec0a7dbc79626ac36ef6ad84c864b80e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2020-08-12 05:17:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI wouldn't want echo_client to be compiled permanently into the Lustre kernel module.  This is mostly debugging code.  Even if the rest of the filesystem is in a module, I'd think that echo_client and probably o2iblnd (because of OFED dependencies) should be kept as separate loadable modules.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "eee412c5c25495046a628a578a1ad83351116f81",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 799,
        "name": "Lustre Gerrit Janitor",
        "email": "lgerrit@linuxhacker.ru",
        "username": "lgerritjanitor",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2020-08-12 05:26:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nInitial testing failed:\n\n> sanity2@ldiskfs+DNE Failure(5183s)\n- 129(dirsize 4096 < 32768 after 93 files) \n\nSucceeded:\n- sanity1@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-slow@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special1@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special1@ldiskfs sanity-special2@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special2@ldiskfs sanity-special3@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special3@ldiskfs sanity-special4@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special4@ldiskfs sanity-special5@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special5@ldiskfs sanity-special6@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special6@ldiskfs sanity-special7@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special7@ldiskfs sanity-special8@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special8@ldiskfs sanity-special9@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special9@ldiskfs sanity-special10@ldiskfs+DNE sanity-special10@ldiskfs sanity1@zfs sanity2@zfs sanity-slow@zfs sanity-special1@zfs sanity-special1@zfs+DNE sanity-special2@zfs sanity-special2@zfs+DNE sanity-special3@zfs sanity-special3@zfs+DNE sanity-special4@zfs sanity-special4@zfs+DNE sanity-special5@zfs sanity-special5@zfs+DNE sanity-special6@zfs sanity-special6@zfs+DNE sanity-special7@zfs sanity-special7@zfs+DNE sanity-special8@zfs sanity-special8@zfs+DNE sanity-special9@zfs sanity-special9@zfs+DNE sanity-special10@zfs sanity-special10@zfs+DNE \n\n(centos7)All results and logs: https://testing-archive.whamcloud.com/gerrit-janitor/10830/results.html",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "1a70f9795e19cfcec4ec172269429e569ddb7fdc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2020-08-12 06:54:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> I wouldn't want echo_client to be compiled permanently into the Lustre kernel module. \n\nNo question that it should be possible to build as a module (or not at all), and that should be the default.\nBut would it matter if someone were to choose a configuration that isn't your personal first choice?\nI do all (almost) all my kernel testing by building a monolithic kernel (no modules) and running \"qemu -kernel /path/bzImage -sda root-image ....\"  It's a lot easier to set up than having to copy modules around, and making sure the modules match the booting kernel.\n\nNote that I'm not suggesting echo_client be part of the lustre module.  They would either be separate modules, or both part of the kernel (or lustre be in-kernel, but echo_client be a module).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
